{%- comment -%}
  Product Variant Picker — renders option selectors.
  Birebir from source: finish selector (swatches) + cabinet type (grid buttons).
  Uses Shopify product.options_with_values.

  Accepts:
  - product: {Object} Shopify product
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- unless product.has_only_default_variant -%}
  <div class="kt-variant-picker" data-variant-picker>
    {%- for option in product.options_with_values -%}
      {%- assign option_name_lower = option.name | downcase -%}
      {%- assign is_color = false -%}
      {%- if option_name_lower == 'color' or option_name_lower == 'colour' or option_name_lower == 'renk' or option_name_lower == 'finish' -%}
        {%- assign is_color = true -%}
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- comment -%}
        Resolve the currently selected option value from the active
        variant so deep-links (?variant=...) and back-button restores
        paint the correct swatch/button on initial render.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {%- assign current_option_value = product.selected_or_first_available_variant.options[forloop.index0] | default: option.selected_value | default: option.values.first -%}

      <fieldset class="kt-variant-picker__group" data-option-index="{{ forloop.index0 }}">
        <legend class="kt-variant-picker__label">
          {{ option.name }}:
          <span class="kt-variant-picker__selected" data-option-selected="{{ forloop.index0 }}">
            {{ current_option_value }}
          </span>
        </legend>

        {%- if is_color -%}
          {%- comment -%}
            Swatch resolution priority (Shopify OS 2.0 metafield-first):
            1. Variant metafield `custom.swatch_color` (hex or CSS color)
               — merchant can override any swatch per variant.
            2. Variant metafield `custom.swatch_image` (image swatch) —
               rendered as the background of the swatch chip.
            3. CSS Named Colors on the option value (e.g. "Black" maps
               natively to rgb(0,0,0) via background-color: valueName).
            4. Hardcoded fallback palette below for brand-specific finish
               names the browser wouldn't understand.
          {%- endcomment -%}
          <div class="kt-variant-picker__swatches">
            {%- for value in option.values -%}
              {%- liquid
                assign matching_variant = nil
                assign option_available = false
                for v in product.variants
                  if v.options contains value
                    if matching_variant == nil
                      assign matching_variant = v
                    endif
                    if v.available
                      assign option_available = true
                      break
                    endif
                  endif
                endfor

                assign swatch_meta_color = nil
                assign swatch_meta_image = nil
                if matching_variant
                  comment
                    Access the .value accessor explicitly and coerce through
                    `strip` so list/JSON coercion of the metafield wrapper
                    object can't accidentally slip raw object syntax into
                    the style attribute. Metafield TYPE `color` returns a
                    hex string (e.g. "#1A1A1A"); `single_line_text_field`
                    returns whatever the merchant typed — and without the
                    sanitization below, a merchant with metafield write
                    access could paste `red; background-image: url(...)`
                    and inject arbitrary CSS into every product page.
                    See the sanitizer on line 102-113 below.
                  endcomment
                  assign swatch_meta_color = matching_variant.metafields.custom.swatch_color.value | strip
                  assign swatch_meta_image = matching_variant.metafields.custom.swatch_image.value
                endif

                comment
                  Sanitize the swatch color before it hits an inline style.
                  Only accept CSS hex (#rgb / #rrggbb / #rrggbbaa). Anything
                  else (including `red`, `rgb(...)`, `var(...)`, free text)
                  is rejected and falls through to the keyword match below.
                  This closes the CSS-injection vector where a write-capable
                  metafield editor could embed `; background-image: url(...)`
                  or `; position: fixed; top: 0;` into every variant picker.

                  Shopify Liquid has no regex — use an alphabet-strip
                  pattern: after `remove`-ing every valid hex char, the
                  candidate must be empty. Then check length is 4/7/9
                  (with the leading `#`).
                endcomment
                if swatch_meta_color != blank
                  assign hex_candidate = swatch_meta_color | downcase
                  assign hex_stripped = hex_candidate
                  assign hex_stripped = hex_stripped | remove: '#'
                  assign hex_stripped = hex_stripped | remove: '0' | remove: '1' | remove: '2' | remove: '3' | remove: '4'
                  assign hex_stripped = hex_stripped | remove: '5' | remove: '6' | remove: '7' | remove: '8' | remove: '9'
                  assign hex_stripped = hex_stripped | remove: 'a' | remove: 'b' | remove: 'c' | remove: 'd' | remove: 'e' | remove: 'f'
                  assign hex_size = hex_candidate | size
                  assign is_hex_color = false
                  if hex_stripped == '' and hex_candidate != ''
                    if hex_size == 4 or hex_size == 7 or hex_size == 9
                      assign hex_first = hex_candidate | slice: 0
                      if hex_first == '#'
                        assign is_hex_color = true
                      endif
                    endif
                  endif
                  unless is_hex_color
                    assign swatch_meta_color = nil
                  endunless
                endif

                assign color_lower = value | downcase | strip
                assign swatch_hex = ''
                case color_lower
                  when 'black'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#1a1a1a'
                  when 'white', 'arctic white'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#faf9f6'
                  when 'gray', 'grey', 'pebble gray'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#a8a29e'
                  when 'charcoal'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#44403c'
                  when 'espresso'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#3C2415'
                  when 'navy', 'navy blue'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#1e3a5f'
                  when 'walnut'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#5D432C'
                  when 'oak', 'natural oak'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#d2b48c'
                  when 'brown'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#6b4e31'
                  when 'beige', 'ivory'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#e8dccc'
                  when 'ice'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#e6eef2'
                  when 'dark'
                    assign swatch_hex = '#1c1917'
                  else
                    assign swatch_hex = ''
                endcase

                assign swatch_style = ''
                if swatch_meta_image != blank
                  assign swatch_image_url = swatch_meta_image | image_url: width: 80
                  assign swatch_style = 'background-image: url(' | append: swatch_image_url | append: '); background-size: cover; background-position: center;'
                elsif swatch_meta_color != blank
                  assign swatch_style = 'background-color: ' | append: swatch_meta_color | append: ';'
                elsif swatch_hex != blank
                  assign swatch_style = 'background-color: ' | append: swatch_hex | append: ';'
                else
                  # Fall back to the CSS color name — modern browsers accept
                  # 140 named colors, which covers most generic palettes.
                  assign swatch_style = 'background-color: ' | append: color_lower | append: ';'
                endif
              -%}

              {%- comment -%}
                A11y — the `<label>` wraps a visually-hidden radio input
                plus a styled `<span>` with no text content. Without an
                accessible name on the input, screen readers announce
                "radio button" with no option value. Reviewer a11y pass
                flags this. Fix: `aria-label` on the input carries the
                option name (+ sold-out status) to assistive tech while
                the `title` attribute continues to serve sighted users
                as a hover tooltip. Keep in sync with the option cell
                below (non-color grid buttons render visible text, so
                they don't need the aria-label treatment).
              {%- endcomment -%}
              {%- capture swatch_a11y_label -%}
                {{ option.name }}: {{ value }}{% unless option_available %} — {{ 'kt.product.sold_out' | t }}{% endunless %}
              {%- endcapture -%}
              <label class="kt-variant-picker__swatch-label{% unless option_available %} kt-variant-picker__swatch-label--soldout{% endunless %}">
                <input
                  type="radio"
                  name="option-{{ option.name | handle }}"
                  value="{{ value | escape }}"
                  aria-label="{{ swatch_a11y_label | strip | escape }}"
                  {% if value == current_option_value %}checked{% endif %}
                  {% unless option_available %}disabled{% endunless %}
                  class="kt-variant-picker__swatch-input visually-hidden"
                  data-option-value
                >
                <span
                  class="kt-variant-picker__swatch"
                  style="{{ swatch_style }}"
                  title="{{ value | escape }}{% unless option_available %} — {{ 'kt.product.sold_out' | t }}{% endunless %}"
                  aria-hidden="true"
                ></span>
              </label>
            {%- endfor -%}
          </div>

        {%- else -%}
          {%- comment -%} Non-color: grid buttons {%- endcomment -%}
          <div class="kt-variant-picker__buttons">
            {%- for value in option.values -%}
              {%- liquid
                assign option_available = false
                for v in product.variants
                  if v.options contains value and v.available
                    assign option_available = true
                    break
                  endif
                endfor
              -%}
              <label class="kt-variant-picker__btn-label{% unless option_available %} kt-variant-picker__btn-label--soldout{% endunless %}">
                <input
                  type="radio"
                  name="option-{{ option.name | handle }}"
                  value="{{ value | escape }}"
                  {% if value == current_option_value %}checked{% endif %}
                  {% unless option_available %}disabled{% endunless %}
                  class="kt-variant-picker__btn-input visually-hidden"
                  data-option-value
                >
                <span class="kt-variant-picker__btn">{{ value }}</span>
              </label>
            {%- endfor -%}
          </div>
        {%- endif -%}
      </fieldset>
    {%- endfor -%}

    {%- comment -%}
      Hidden select used purely as a variant-JSON registry and change
      target for product-form.js. It is NOT a form field — we deliberately
      omit `name="id"` so it cannot collide with the real hidden input
      inside `{%- form 'product' -%}` (see snippets/product-form.liquid).
      That hidden input is the single source of truth for the variant id
      sent to /cart/add; product-form.js rewrites its value whenever this
      select changes (data-variant-select listener).
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <select class="visually-hidden" data-variant-select aria-label="{{ 'kt.product.variant' | t | default: 'Variant' }}" tabindex="-1" aria-hidden="true">
      {%- for variant in product.variants -%}
        <option
          value="{{ variant.id }}"
          {% if variant == product.selected_or_first_available_variant %}selected{% endif %}
          {% unless variant.available %}disabled{% endunless %}
          {%- comment -%}
            Double-quoted attr + `| escape` is required. Shopify's
            `| json` encodes for JSON string context but does NOT
            HTML-entity-encode `"`, `&`, `<`. A variant with a
            title containing `'` (e.g. "Men's Large") would otherwise
            break out of a single-quoted attribute — attribute-
            breakout XSS. Double-quote + escape closes both paths.
          {%- endcomment -%}
          data-variant-json="{{ variant | json | escape }}"
        >
          {{ variant.title }}
        </option>
      {%- endfor -%}
    </select>
  </div>

  {%- comment -%}
    JS-off fallback. Our primary variant UI above is a set of radio/swatch
    fieldsets that talk to product-form.js; with JS disabled they do not
    update the hidden `name="id"` input inside the product form and the
    customer is stuck on whichever variant happened to be active at page
    load. The pattern below — a visible-only-when-JS-is-off native
    <select name="id"> that posts to /cart/add directly via its own
    form — is the standard OS 2.0 progressive-enhancement pattern.
    The picker itself is wrapped in <noscript> so it is *hidden when
    JS is on*, preventing duplicate controls from conflicting. The
    form's submit button is labeled "Select variant" and relies on
    the browser's native form POST to the cart — no JS needed.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <noscript>
    <form action="{{ routes.cart_add_url }}" method="post" enctype="multipart/form-data" class="kt-variant-picker__nojs">
      <label for="VariantNoJs-{{ product.id }}" class="kt-variant-picker__nojs-label">
        {{ 'kt.product.variant' | t | default: 'Variant' }}
      </label>
      <select id="VariantNoJs-{{ product.id }}" name="id" class="kt-variant-picker__nojs-select">
        {%- for variant in product.variants -%}
          <option
            value="{{ variant.id }}"
            {% if variant == product.selected_or_first_available_variant %}selected{% endif %}
            {% unless variant.available %}disabled{% endunless %}
          >
            {{ variant.title }}
            {%- unless variant.available %} — {{ 'kt.product.sold_out' | t | default: 'sold out' }}{% endunless -%}
            {%- if variant.available %} — {{ variant.price | money }}{% endif -%}
          </option>
        {%- endfor -%}
      </select>
      <button type="submit" class="kt-variant-picker__nojs-submit">
        {{ 'kt.product.add_to_cart' | t | default: 'Add to cart' }}
      </button>
    </form>
  </noscript>
{%- endunless -%}
